727737f-a.title: Queens: Queens Boulevard - 55th Avenue
727737f-a.text:
Oueers Boulevard, north side, west of Fifty-fifth Ave., to
Broadway, showing in 4 views the Old Presbyterian Church and
Cemetery of Newtown. The Church was destroyed by fire in May 1929.
iee other views. The rest of the buildinaein this view were all
demolished by Mar. 1, 1931. This churcn was erected in 1787 on
site of a former one destroyed by the British during the Revolutionary
Var. Dr. John P. Knox was pastor from 1855 to 1882. At this
time square pews with little doors were installed.
Jan. 1923.
Views 1 and 2
View 3: July 1925
View 4: Oct. 1928.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection

727733f-a.title: Queens: Queens Boulevard - 55th Avenue
727733f-a.text:
Queens Boulevard, east side, from 55th Avenue (left) to
hnear 56th Avenue, showing the area in two successive views.
These homes appear on maps as early as 1873. The first three
homes from the left (view 1) were then owned by H. Geisling;
the little house to the right of these, by one G.B.; and the
house with the dormer windows, as well as the one adjoining it
on the right, by Mrs. Raymond. To the right of that, standing
in the direct path of the proposed extension of 55th Road, is
the J. Casey house. The two small houses in the center of view
1 are on the direct line of 55th Avenue, when the latter will be
extended here; the houses on the left will then ocoupy the W.E.
corner of the intersection.
P. L. Sperr  July 2, 1935
NO REPRODUCTIONS  Views 1,2
N,~ 2307

727735f-b.text:
Cueens Boulevard, north side, between 55th Avenue and Broadway,
whowing the Presbyterian First Church of Newtown, erected in 1787.
Tt was damaged by fire in 1928. A new, granite edifice was erected
for the congregation in 1893, directly across the street from this
structure.
View 1: Arthur White  About 1920
